results.notes:
On the ground near an old apple tree. For 19 years I have spread scraps of morels and water used to clean spores from my dehydrator on the ground in this spot. However, I believe that none of the spores I had intentionally spread in this spot represented this particular species. I have almost certainly spread spores of M. angusticpes in this spot. But I think this mushroom represents a species other than M. angusticeps. I doubt this mushroom represents a species of Morchella sect. Morchella; the deep vertical channels with cross ridges point toward sect. Distantes.

Between 15-19 years ago, when I first moved into the house at this location, I tried planting two different morel grow kits. I don’t recall planting any in this particular spot, but I may have. Once of the kits came in a box that showed a photo of morels that looked like this one. I remember planting the kit in a different location. But, I think I may have split the contents and buried small portions in a couple other spots, including where I found this mushroom. This idea makes the most sense to me.

Scoped some smash-mounted material from both a ridge and a pit (photos 5-9); no spores found. Hoping for spores to drop.

Basidiocarp fan- to hoof-shaped, perennial, developing new pores each year. Cap rough, cracked, and green-black in color with a brown margin and white edge. Etymology!

results.notes:
Large fruiting on well rotted Maple(partially submerged in stream). 2-5cm tall, light brown and minutely pimpled with a Pronounced white stem, multiple fruiting bodies with folded apothecia(like Otidea). Flesh is pliant and not very fragile. Once dried outer context of apothecia is gray and pruinose in appearance. Harvested multiple fruiting bodies and dried for herbarium.
Cap: drying gray, hirsute, fuzzy. Multiple specimens with irregular folds.
Stem: smooth, swollen at base, becoming orange/yellow at extreme base once dried(images added).

UPDATE on 4/29/20: Performed microscopy-multiple images added in side bar.
Spores: oblong, large, with single large oil droplet=Helvella.
Keyed to Helvella macropus group which states “on wood/sticks or soil”(descriptions/differences and comments on Helvella fibrosa and Helvella cupuliformis under Helvella macropus in key). Both H. cupuliformis and H. fibrosa have smooth, rounded stems that dry yellow, however, H. fibrosa separates/splits into folds and irregular caps at maturity(which all of my collection did, similar to Otidea in appearance). ID from another member on iNaturalist(Fred Rhoades) claims H. cupuliformis has shorter stems than H. fibrosa, but all of the multiple sources I have reviewed show the converse(H. fibrosa having the shorter stem between the two). That fact, coupled with the folded, dark mature caps and less narrow spores points to H. fibrosa. DNA analysis may be the only way to get exact ID for these.
